<sn><md>### Specifying Commits{.text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Absolute Hash{.fg-teal .text-center}

You can use the full or partial commit hash to compare two commits:

```bash
git diff 4f8a3c1 7b9d2e5
```

Here, `4f8a3c1` and `7b9d2e5` are the unique commit hashes.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Relative to HEAD{.fg-orange .text-center}

You can also reference commits relative to the `HEAD`:

```bash
git diff HEAD~3 HEAD~1
```

This compares the state of the repository three commits before `HEAD` with the state one commit before `HEAD`.
:::

:::
</md></sn><sn><md>### Comparing Specific Files{.text-center}

If you want to view changes only for a specific file between two commits:

```bash
git diff commit1 commit2 filename
```

Example:

```bash
git diff HEAD~2 HEAD~1 app.js
```

This shows only the changes in `app.js`.</md></sn><sn><md>### Viewing Changed File Names Only{.text-center}

If you’re interested in just the list of changed files between two commits:

```bash
git diff commit1 commit2 --name-only
```

Example:

```bash
git diff 4f8a3c1 7b9d2e5 --name-only
```

This outputs only the filenames that were modified.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Viewing File Names with Change Status{.text-center}

To see not just the filenames but also the type of changes (`A` for added, `M` for modified, `D` for deleted):

```bash
git diff commit1 commit2 --name-status
```

Example:

```bash
git diff HEAD~3 HEAD~1 --name-status
```

Sample output:

```
M   index.html
A   styles.css
D   old_script.js
```</md></sn><sn><md>### Summary{.text-center}

* Use **absolute hashes** or **relative references** (`HEAD~n`) to specify commits.
* Use `git diff commit1 commit2 filename` to see changes in a specific file.
* Use `--name-only` to list changed files.
* Use `--name-status` to list changed files along with their status (added/modified/deleted).

This makes `git diff` a versatile tool for reviewing the history and changes in a project.
